SIMPLE: eloquence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eloquence
<hw>El"o*quence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧loquence</ets>, L. <ets>eloquentia</ets>, fr.
<ets>eloquens</ets>. See <er>Eloquent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Fluent, forcible, elegant, and persuasive speech in public; the
power of expressing strong emotions in striking and appropriate language
either spoken or written, thereby producing conviction or
persuasion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Eloquence</qex> is speaking out . . . out of the abundance of
the heart.</q> <rj><qau>Hare.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Whatever produces the effect of moving and
persuasive speech.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Silence that spoke and <qex>eloquence</qex> of eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hearts of men are their books; events are their tutors; great
actions are their <qex>eloquence</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is eloquently uttered or
written.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, let my books be then the <qex>eloquence</qex>⟦br⟧
And dumb presagers of my speaking breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Oratory; rhetoric.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eloquent</ent>⟦br⟧
